This is a simple monoalphabetic substitution cipher.

============================================================
SOLUTION NOTES
============================================================

Cipher type:  Monoalphabetic substitution
              Each cipher letter maps to exactly one plaintext letter.
              Spaces and punctuation are left unchanged.

Source text:  Daniel 5:5-12 (King James Bible)
              The passage describes the "writing on the wall" during
              King Belshazzar's feast, interpreted by Daniel.

Archaic spellings preserved in the ciphertext:
  - HYS  (archaic "HIS")
  - HYM  (archaic "HIM")
  - ABOVT (archaic "ABOUT")
  These reflect early printed English orthography and are not errors.

Substitution key (cipher letter -> plaintext letter):
  A->C   B->I   C->O   D->V   E->Y   F->B
  G->L   H->K   I->F   J->T   K->Q   L->M
  M->A   N->D   O->Z   P->H   Q->P   R->S
  S->J   T->N   U->U   V->R   W->G   X->E
  Y->W   Z->X

Codeword:  OTHELLO

Method:    decrypt_stage01.py
  1. Builds quadgram log-probability statistics from ../misc/kjv.txt.
  2. Starts hill-climbing from a frequency-analysis initial key
     (most-frequent cipher letter -> 'E', etc.).
  3. Refines by trying all 325 pairwise key swaps; keeps any
     swap that improves the quadgram score.
  4. Solved on the first restart (no random restarts needed).
